I believe the main issue is from validators using wrong cache data.  There are some pretty major issues with how the scoring is working right now. The biggest problem is that each validator has its own local cache of miner distribution data (like IP-to-country, country counts, etc.), and they’re not synced. That means different validators can calculate totally different uniqueness scores for the exact same miner. On top of that, if their cache is empty, they fall back to backup data — but they might pull that at different times, which adds even more inconsistency. Plus, the way they detect IP types (like whether it’s a datacenter or not) and geolocation can vary too, depending on when/where the lookup happens or the database version. Some specific cases highlight this: like one validator ranking a Ghana miner super high while another gives a much lower score to a similar miner from Algeria — all because they have different views of the miner landscape. Same goes for Vietnam and Finland anomalies. Bottom line: the math behind the scoring is fine, but it’s built on data that’s totally unsynced across validators, which breaks the fairness. It really needs a shared data source or at least better cache handling to fix this.

This is **NOT** the score calculation but a component of it. Note how `uniqueness_score` is an input to that function. That component is the most important. The hypothesis in this is mostly that the ip databases are potentially out of sync. This is an potential issue in theory, but in practice the database is updated every 30 minutes on all validators. That means that score discrepancies should not be very significant, and if they are then something else is failing.

The local caches are purely a memory cache so that we don't need to read from disk so much. The maxmind database is updated every 30 minutes, and the cache data is updated every time the neuron calls `/broadcast/miners` which is approximately every 5-10 minutes.

The only thing that I can think of that can add significant entropy to the scores is the grace window for miner responses (currently 45 sec) which is some cases can be longer
If that score is not updated that means either your miner is misconfigured, or you were using custom cheating logic that we blocked :chloe1:

Hello @tpn・65 !

We have an extremely exciting announcement and are posting it here first so you're the first to know.

TL;DR: we have completely redesigned the TPN subnet to scale from ~250 nodes to **uncapped scalability**. This will change EVERYTHING for miners. We are launching next week and you should be prepared!

Long version:

We have been secretly (but publicly, if you were keeping an eye on our Github) designing and implementing a huge upgrade to TPN.

Our old subnet setup had 2 kinds of nodes: validators and miners. Due to Bittensor limits this meant we could never offer VPN connections from more than ~250 locations.

Our new setup will have 3 kinds of nodes: validators, mining pools, and workers. Mining pools are Bittensor miners that offer the VPN connections of downstream worker machines. The workers are lightweight machines that do not have a Bittensor neuron and purely serve their connections to a mining pool.

This exciting new setup will allow the network to grow from a cool Bittensor subnet to a large federated decentralised network that happens to be powered by a Bittensor subnet.

A lot of things are on our roadmap for the coming months:

- Launch the new subnet topology
- Launch a developer portal where developers can pay for VPN credits
- Launch payment infrastructure so mining pools can easily pay their workers (even if they do not own them)
- Launch partner VPN apps that use Bittensor for real consumer use

Be advised: the next weeks are likely to be turbulent! We are deploying an innovative and never-done-before decentralised VPN network. We'll rely on your patience and feeback to hunt down issues as we find them.

Stay tuned in this channel for updates.

Onward! 🚀
